1. Module Formats and Environment
- Modern JavaScript supports ES Modules (ESM) natively in browsers and Node.js. File extensions: .js or .mjs. Node/Ecosystem: Node may require .mjs or package.json type:module to treat .js as ESM.
- Module files must be served with a JavaScript MIME type (e.g., text/javascript) or browsers will refuse to execute them under strict MIME checking.
- Use <script type="module"> to load modules in browsers; modules are deferred by default.

2. Exporting Features
- Export at top-level only. Usable forms: named exports (export const name = ...; export function fn() {...}) and aggregated exports (export { a, b, c }).
- Exportable entities: const, let, var, functions, classes. Cannot export local variables declared inside functions.
- Exports are live bindings: the importing module sees updates to exported bindings; imported binding identifiers are read-only in the importing module (cannot be re-assigned locally).

3. Importing Features
- Use import { a, b } from "./module.js" or default imports. Module specifier must be a path or absolute URL, unless mapped using import maps.
- Relative specifiers (./ or ../) resolve relative to importing module's base URL. In browsers, absolute URLs and same-origin rules apply.
- Imported values are read-only views of the exporting module's bound value; object properties can be mutated but the binding cannot be reassigned.

4. Import Maps
- Import maps provide a mapping from bare specifiers to absolute or relative URLs via a JSON object placed in a <script type="importmap"> element.
- Import maps apply to the document scope and replace specifiers during resolution. They do not apply to workers or worklets by the specification (implementation caveat).
- Keys without trailing slash are exact-match; keys with trailing slash allow prefix mapping behavior.

5. MIME and Server Requirements
- Servers must provide Content-Type header that includes a JavaScript MIME type for module files. Typical header: Content-Type: text/javascript; charset=utf-8.
- .mjs may not be served correctly by all servers; configure server to serve .mjs as text/javascript or use .js with package.json type:module.

6. Implementation & Best Practices
- Prefer explicit relative paths for portability; when using bare specifiers use import maps or bundler resolution.
- Use single export list at end for readability when exporting many items: export { a, b, c }.
- Prefer tree-shaking-friendly patterns: use named exports rather than exporting a single object with multiple properties.
- For cross-environment compatibility, ensure package.json includes "type":"module" for ESM .js files in Node.js, or use .mjs extensions.

SUPPLEMENTARY DETAILS

Technical specifications and implementation details:
- Module resolution: browsers follow URL resolution rules; Node uses package exports and package.json fields when resolving bare specifiers.
- Dynamic import: import(specifier) returns a Promise resolving to module namespace object; use for code-splitting, lazy-loading.
- Circular dependencies: handled via live bindings; modules may observe partially-initialized exports during circular load; design to avoid heavy init logic at module top-level.

